I started ‘studying’ cocktails when I was about 14 or thereabouts. My mum bought me a bunch of very basic drink books to whet my appetite as I went down the rabbit hole of this weird and wonderful world of mixed drinks. Thanks Ma 🫶🏻

Did I mention I was fourteen? 🤨🙄😱

These two books here were the first two books I ever owned and I was so proud to read them incessantly, memorizing each recipe like it was an ancient treasure, despite the fact that, well as you can see, some of these recipes sound downright hideous 😬

Sambuca, Benedictine, Glayva (anyone remember Glayva? Anyone heard of Glayva? No? Well that’s why I had the Drinks Dictionary duh!), orange and lemon juices. In the same glass! Hard pass for me 🤢

I would try and recreate many of these drinks in the Australian Woman’s Weekly Cocktail Guide when mum had friends over and I’m sure my renditions were awful. Not that she ever told me so but we both know the truth. 

And without the Drinks Dictionary how would I ever know the difference between Grand Marnier and Grande Champagne? Is that just a big bottle of Champagne? 🤷‍♂️

Or how Barolo is not the same as Barley Wine. Hey, I was fourteen, pipe down! Or what Chartreuse was. Or what was in a Charlie Chaplin cocktail. Anyways, I found these two books recently online and I’m happy they’re back in my possession, all these years later so I can look back on what I’ve learnt and where it all started at the tender age of, um, yeah fourteen. Nice to reflect on that from time to time 🤔

About a decade ago, when we opened The Daily (RIP) in New York, this humble, tattered little rolodex (remember those?) would become the very backbone of the entire concept; a lilliputian cocktail bar in Nolita that had a small menu that changed every single day and a place that would foster some great talent behind its bar, most notably @hopignacio, who would carve out his name here and well, the rest is history. Same for @masanyc but he, too, was already making history at Saxon + Parole at the same time.

Now I’m bringing the rolodex back at our new space on Miami Beach, opening in a matter of weeks. This rolodex contains about 400+ classic drinks that have each been tested and retested over the last decade; their recipes evolving in their own way as trends and tastes and other factors evolve too. 

I believe it’s crucial that any bar or bartender worth their salt can make (almost) any classic drink on request and so having this resource literally at the bartender’s fingertips is a great, tangible, interactive way to learn these important foundations and build from there. Are there more efficient ways this can be presented and implemented? No doubt. Is it a more fun and personal approach that still gets the desired result? You bet.

The Formula One is again coming to Miami this May 5-7th for the second time and Sweet Liberty has an official bar on the grounds once again with an expected daily attendance of between 25-30K people. Our bar was very successful last year and while this year our footprint is even larger, we're still located in the yacht marina area, one of the busiest places on campus. We got killed last year but boy did we have a blast!

We are looking for bartenders and barbacks to work with us for anywhere from 3-5 days depending on your role and duties. Here’s the scoop:

-You will be paid a very generous hourly rate for a minimum 10+ hour day. Even if it gets rained out, you will still make that minimum. On top of that, our crew last year made several thousand in tips on top of that hourly.
-It will be a very high volume environment as we are in a general admission area
-It is mostly a day time gig, with the work day running from about 8am-8pm depending on the day. It's long days in the hot sun so be ready for that
-We want people that are fun, engaging, professional and are not afraid of some hard work. No prima donnas or startenders!

We will take on anyone from anywhere as long as you have a valid US working visa. You will, however, be required to get yourself to Miami and sort out your own accomadations, travel to and from the event and all expenses. 

You will also get paid what I consider to be very well for the work and you’ll get to experience the incredible race atmosphere as a working participant. Our bar is 50 feet from the track!

When curating my first menu for Sweet, I almost fell over when I came across a drink that had a moniker that just seemed too good to be true. Seriously, there’s a ‘Florida Cocktail’? 😱🤯🤩

It contained rum, crème de menthe, lime & pineapple juice, which I went about reinterpreting in my own unique way. This simple recipe called out to be made fluffy in my mind and so here we are kids with my own rendition of Embury’s recipe, in all its long, neon, delicious, vibrant, minty glory. How good is a perfectly made classic Old Fashioned? Such a perfect drink that just hits all the right notes. 

I like to use a stronger base whiskey to stand up to the dilution from stirring (plus the fact that it then sits on ice). Some faves include Old Forester 100, Knob Creek, Wild Turkey 101, Baker’s and several others.

That higher proof also cuts through the sweetener too. 

Speaking of which . . . . Of course there’s the ubiquitous sugar cube or simple syrup which are totally fine. But for a little more richness, you can’t get mad at using a deft hand with some agave, honey, maple or piloncillo too 🙌

And for bitters, well, the choices are myriad these days. Far too many to mention here but the stalwart of Angostura always does the trick for me, though we sometimes blend this with some other brands or infuse it for added complexity. 

Serve this over a big chunk of ice and you’ve got yourself some delicious liquid alchemy right there kids! 👊🥃😄

It’s been a long time coming but I couldn’t leave New Zealand this time without getting a Ta Moko (tribal family tattoo) that I’ve been thinking about since getting my other arm done almost a decade ago. This art form is a deep form of expression and identity to the Māori of this land, of which my mother is extremely proud of her heritage and has always tried to instill this legacy into me too. Its power and importance has never been lost on me and to be able to immortalize it in this beautiful way is both overwhelming, surreal and real. 

As tradition dictates, to get this kind of moko done cannot be done by anyone that doesn’t understand your ‘Whakapapa’ (family geonology) and we found an amazing conduit today named Henare that knew about this lineage and how to express it through his beautiful art and skill on my body that will last in finitum. I am absolutely in awe of his artistry and his 25 year dedication to his craft and it was an incredible journey with him today as I went through some extreme extreme pain to be able to remember this moment forever. I am also so proud of what you delivered Henare Brooking, you were a kind and patient artist, historian and teacher and I will forever be in your debt. Kia Ora my bro!

And the fact that Gaby, my mother and my dearest Aunty Violet were there as witnesses and much needed support when things got really tough near the end meant the world and helped me understand and navigate this deep and noble and powerful story that is the indigenous Māori of Aotearoa 👊🙌❤️🙇‍♂️🫶🏻

Thank you for all the lessons Ma ❤️
